<FONT CLASS="ArticleSource"><BIG>Editorial:</BIG></FONT> 
<FONT CLASS="ArticleHead"><BIG>On Spells and Silly Item Tags</BIG></FONT>
<FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </FONT><FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthor">Tann</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleTime>12/08/2001 01:24 PM CST</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=LEFT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleText>
I'm not sure exactly why VI continues to recycle bad ideas with each expansion, but it certainly seems to be the case. Placing post-49 spells on mobs as loot completely annoys me.  Honestly, you'd think not one of the designers has ever played a caster, and simply doesn't realize how sub-classes develop as players with certain spells are desired over those without.  They should have learned their lesson with the problems guilds and players encountered when trying to find copies of Malo after Kunark was released.  Guilds were decimated and friendships ruined as shamans with and without these spells dealt with issues of jealousy and anger.  They've adjusted the drop tables on these spells a few times now, and there are still shamans that haven't been able to find them.  <p>Just put the damn spells on vendors and let people buy them already.  Maybe the concept of a caster class has been lost.  They CAST spells, and by not making them available,  players become frustrated and less effective.   It's not as if VI has never realized a feature isn't working or desired; they did realize at some point that research was a waste of time and energy.  Now if they would only take this next step and realize that spells as loot is also asinine, it would make for a much happier caster community.<p>And as long as I'm complaining about features that should be programmed out of existence, it might be nice if they revisited the no-drop issue.  I've never really understood why item &quot;A&quot; should get this designation, while item &quot;B&quot; (a better item) doesn't.  Admittedly, the concept had merit before the Kunark launch when real estate was at a minimum, and farming of items was rampant.  But with each new expansion, new mob, and new loot, older items that are trivial or junk by today's standards have maintained their &quot;no drop&quot; status.  VI has revisited mobs and re-tuned in certain circumstances (i.e. Cazic Thule, Innoruuk), which was a nice idea, but the re-tuning of loot also included a re-tuning of the mobs. I can't think of one instance where a no-drop item has simply been reclassified as normal loot.  <p>Unfortunately, the re-tuning of mobs was done was very selectively--in most cases just the one mob--which also turned out to be a bad idea.  The gear in Fear is basically junk and destroyed by guilds able to kill CT. By re-tuning CT and not the rest of Fear, mid-level and newer guilds lost the benefit of having a training grounds, areas where they could go to perfect techniques and strategies that older, more established guilds have developed and learned.  I feel sorry for these newer guilds; they've missed out on the thrill of killing a god, of challenging themselves and their guilds in a series of battles and raids that get exponentially harder. But they can forget about CT--the uber guilds covet his loot, and might makes right in Norrath.  <p>The idea of having a zone that both uber and  non-uber guilds can use is a good one, but only if both can <br>benefit somewhat equally.   Fear gear, excluding CT, is hopelessly outdated--yet it's still no drop.  Leave items lore if you are concerned about farming and twinking,  but &quot;no drop&quot; is an outdated concept. There are too many viable alternatives--gear and items that are actually desired that aren't no-drop--to believe that the idea should be continued.
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
